songs.label: Iso/Columbia
songs.comments: "Look up here, I'm in heaven. I've got scars that can't be seen." From David Bowie's final album, released on his birthday - three days ago.
songs.title: Lazarus

songs.album: The Rise And Fall Of Ziggy Stardust And The Spiders From Mars
songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: The song is generally interpreted as alluding to fellow glam rock icon Marc Bolan.
songs.title: Lady Stardust

songs.label: EMI
songs.comments: The final version that became "Under Pressure" evolved from a jam session that Bowie had with the band at Queen's studio in Montreux, Switzerland.
songs.title: Under Pressure

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Bowie's performance of "'Heroes'" on June 6, 1987 at the German Reichstag in West Berlin was considered a catalyst to the eventual fall of the Berlin Wall.
songs.title: "Heroes"

songs.label: EMI
songs.comments: Stevie Ray Vaughan played the guitar solo at the end of the song. "Let's Dance" was one of his best-selling singles to date.
songs.title: Let's Dance

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: The song was a massive breakthrough in the United States, where glam rock had never really become very popular outside the major cities.
songs.title: Young Americans

songs.label: EMI
songs.comments: Bowie claimed the song was inspired by Little Richard, and it maintains the album's theme of a struggle between God and man.
songs.title: Modern Love

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: David Bowie was a huge Elvis fan and wrote "Golden Years" with the intention of giving it to him to perform, but he reportedly refused the song. Elvis died two years later.
songs.title: Golden Years

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Written by Bowie, Carlos Alomar and John Lennon, it reached Number 1 on the Billboard Hot 100 during the week of 20 September 1975. The song is included in The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll.
songs.title: Fame

songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: The lyrics have been interpreted as a look back at Bowie's severe mood swings during his drug addiction phase while living in Los Angeles from 1975 to 1976, with the line "Thank God Heaven left us standing on our feet" suggesting the singer's gratitude for making it through that period.
songs.title: Beauty & The Beast

songs.label: Virgin
songs.comments: "Waiting for the Man" was written by Lou Reed for the Velvet Underground. Bowie covered this song and recorded it live at his show in Santa Monica's Civic Auditorium in 1972.
songs.title: Waiting For The Man (Live)

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: According to Bowie, it was "a smorgasbord of imagined Americana", with a protagonist inspired by Iggy Pop, and the title being an allusion to author Jean Genet.
songs.title: The Jean Genie

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Bowie was a great Velvet Underground fan and wrote the song in tribute to the band and Lou Reed.
songs.title: Queen Bitch

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Bowie based it on friend Iggy Pop's descriptions of revolutionaries he had known as a youth in Michigan.
songs.title: Panic In Detroit

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Cited as his most-covered track, it was effectively Bowie's farewell to the glam rock movement that he had helped pioneer.
songs.title: Rebel Rebel

songs.album: The Rise And Fall Of Ziggy Stardust And The Spiders From Mars
songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: The name Stardust was inspired by the Legendary Stardust Cowboy. A live version recorded at Santa Monica Civic Auditorium, 20 October 1972 was released on Santa Monica '72 and Live Santa Monica '72.
songs.title: Ziggy Stardust

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Released by Bowie in 1973. The song is a cover version of The Who's original track from 1964.
songs.title: I Can't Explain

songs.label: MCA
songs.comments: Title song of the 1982 film Cat People. The song was written by Bowie with producer Giorgio Moroder.
songs.title: Cat People (Putting Out Fire)

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: Bowie described Ashes to Ashes as his way to wrap up the seventies. The song has a very innovative video, directed by Bowie and David Mallet.
songs.title: Ashes To Ashes

songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: The song is notable for juxtaposing an uplifting guitar and synthesizer-led instrumental track with Bowie's withdrawn lyrics.
songs.title: Sound And Vision

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: The track was inspired by an episode in which Iggy Pop, during a drug-fuelled period at Bowie's LA home, hallucinated and believed the television set was swallowing his girlfriend.
songs.title: TVC15

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: The lyrics are often seen as a manifesto for his chameleonic personality, the frequent change of the world today, and frequent reinventions of his musical style throughout the 1970s.
songs.title: Changes

songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: The simple piano style is often compared to The Beatles' "Martha My Dear".
songs.title: Oh! You Pretty Things

songs.album: The Rise And Fall Of Ziggy Stardust And The Spiders From Mars
songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: Bowie is rumored to have chosen the length of time, five years, as a result of a dream in which his deceased father told him he must never fly again and would die in five years.
songs.title: Five Years

songs.label: RCA
songs.comments: The song details Ziggy Stardust's final collapse as an old, washed-up rock star and, as such, was also the closing number of the Ziggy Stardust live show.
songs.title: Rock 'n' Roll Suicide [Live]

songs.album: The Man Who Sold The World
songs.label: Mercury
songs.comments: Originally released in 1974. Performed by Nirvana at their 1993 MTV Unplugged and introduced it to a new audience
songs.title: The Man Who Sold The World

songs.album: The Rise And Fall Of Ziggy Stardust And The Spiders From Mars
songs.label: RCA Victor
songs.comments: The lyrics describe Ziggy Stardust bringing a message of hope to Earth's youth through the radio, salvation by an alien 'Starman'.
songs.title: Starman

songs.label: Mercury/Philips
songs.comments: The song is about the launch of Major Tom, a fictional astronaut, and was released during a period of great interest in space flight. The United States' Apollo 11 mission would launch 5 days later, and would become the first manned moon landing another 5 days later.
songs.title: Space Oddity
